Researchers at the Technical University of Braunschweig, Germany, used peppermint plants in a series of mulching and fumigation experiments .
They found that nicotine was frequently used as an insecticide until it was banned by the European Union in 2009 because of its toxicity .
But a surprisingly large number of food crops and plant-derived products still contain very high levels of nicotine in them, despite none being allowed in insecticides .